      "url": "http://www.mercurynews.com/whats-next-for-cambridge-analytica-and-the-facebook-data-it-collected",
      "title": "What's next for Cambridge Analytica and the Facebook data it collected?",
      "body": "Now that Cambridge Analytica is closing down, what happens to all the data it collected?\n\nThe political data consulting firm at the center of the Facebook privacy scandal remains under investigation in the U.K., and Facebook has said it deferred to British officials but is waiting to conduct its own probe into whether the firm retained the data of tens of millions of Facebook users it obtained without permission.\n\n\"Even if the name plate on the door changes, we are still able to pursue the former directors of SCL & Cambridge Analytica,\" Damian Collins, a member of the British Parliament, tweeted Thursday.\n\n\"This doesn't change our commitment and determination to understand exactly what happened and make sure it doesn't happen again,\" a Facebook spokesman said Thursday. \"We are continuing with our investigation in cooperation with the relevant authorities.\"\n\nCambridge Analytica announced Wednesday that it and parent SCL Elections are both shutting down.\n\n\"The siege of media coverage has driven away virtually all of the Company's customers and suppliers,\" Cambridge Analytica said in its announcement, noting that it \"has been vilified for activities that are not only legal, but also widely accepted as a standard component of online advertising in both the political and commercial arenas.\"\n\nCambridge Analytica is said to have obtained the information of Facebook users who used a personality quiz app, and that of those users' friends, designed by Cambridge University researcher Aleksandr Kogan. Kogan initially collected the data for research, but later said he informed users of his intention to sell the data.\n\nThe data collection was first reported a couple of years ago, but media reports in mid-March -- bolstered by claims by a former Cambridge Analytica employee -- blew the scandal wide open and moved Facebook's handling of user data into the spotlight once again.\n\nCambridge Analytica was funded by Republican donor Robert Mercer and once had Steve Bannon, former White House chief strategist, as its vice president. The firm used psychometrics -- which nowadays involves building psychological profiles partly based on people's social media activity -- to try to influence the way people vote. The campaigns of President Trump and others used Cambridge Analytica data.\n\nDespite the official shutdown, though, the Mercer family and executives at Cambridge Analytica and SCL have moved to create a new firm called Emerdata in recent months, the New York Times reports, citing British records. The newspaper also reported that its anonymous sources said those officials are considering selling off the combined company's data and intellectual property.\n\nCambridge Analytica has not responded to a request for comment Thursday about what will happen to the data it collected. Last month, contrary to the media reports that brought the scandal to light, it said deleted the data it had obtained from GSR (Kogan's firm) after being told by Facebook that it was improperly collected, and was \"searching for and removing any of its derivatives in our system.\"",
